SleepSchedulQ1: üí¨ Have you ever noticed that you tend to sleep more on your day off ‚Äì like a public holiday or the weekend?
SleepSchedulQ2:
üóìGetting enough and catching up on lost sleep is important. But many people will find that they feel better rested if they wake up and go to sleep at the same time each day.



ü•±Our bodies can struggle to adapt to a change in sleep schedule. Sleeping later on weekends usually won‚Äôt fully make up for too little sleep during the week. It can also make it more difficult to get up on Monday.

üßê Here are some examples of regular, 9-hour sleep schedules. Which of these examples do you think could help promote a healthy sleep habit?
SleepSchedulQ3:
‚è∞There are several strategies you can use to help manage a regular sleep schedule. One useful tip is to set an alarm clock. Alarms help us wake up in the morning, but we can use them to remind us to go to bed on time as well! 

üöøAnother helpful strategy is setting a regular bedtime routine. This could involve taking a shower, tidying your bedroom, or reading a book.

Let‚Äôs look at an example. Suppose a friend told you: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm very particular about my sleep, and I keep the same schedule every week. I go to bed at 9pm every night on the dot. The only exception is Wednesdays when I catch up with friends. I go to bed at 10pm.‚Äù

üßêWhat do you think about this example?

SleepCaffineQ2:
‚òïÔ∏èThe caffeine in coffee can block some of the chemicals in our brains that make us feel sleepy. This can trick our bodies into feeling alert and awake.

‚ö†Ô∏è While there are times we may want to feel awake, one danger of coffee is that it can prevent us from getting a good night‚Äôs sleep. This also isn‚Äôt just true of coffee, many things can contain caffeine.

SleepCaffineQ3:
üïêCaffeine can also stay in our bodies longer than we expect. It can take as much as 7 hours for our bodies to remove half the caffeine we consume from our brain.

üéÇAging can also alter how fast we process caffeine. The older we are, the longer it can take our brain and body to remove it.

Here‚Äôs an example. Suppose a friend told you: ‚ÄúI love coffee, but I can‚Äôt drink it too close to bed. I have my last cup at about 5pm as soon as I get home from work. That way, it won‚Äôt interfere with my sleep.‚Äù

üßêWhat do you think about this example?

üè•In fact, not getting enough sleep can also impact our health. Here‚Äôs a list of different health issues. Which of these do you think are related to not getting enough sleep?
SleepHoursQ3:
That‚Äôs right! In fact, all of these health issues are somehow related to how much sleep we get. Every major system and organ in our body is impacted when we don‚Äôt get enough sleep.


üí§Most major health organizations suggest that we get at least 7 hours of sleep per night. How much sleep you need, however, varies depending on who you are. Children, for example, typically need more sleep than their parents.

üõèThere‚Äôs a difference between our sleep duration (how long we sleep for) and sleep opportunity (how long we spend in bed). If someone struggles to fall asleep, or wakes up during the night, they may need to spend more time in bed to get enough sleep.

TreatAnecdotesQ1: üí¨ Have you ever had a friend rave to you about something like a restaurant or a movie ‚Äî only to be disappointed when you tried it yourself?
TreatAnecdotesQ2:
When someone tells you about their experience with something, that story is called an anecdote, and they aren‚Äôt always reliable.

Note: the button to continue will only appear after 10 seconds on the page. Please read the following carefully. 


‚ÅâÔ∏è How does that work?

‚ö†Ô∏è The danger of anecdotes is that they assume what‚Äôs true for one person should be true for everyone. 


Here‚Äôs an example:

Suppose a friend told you: ‚ÄúMy cousin is a really fast sprinter, and only buys shoes with thin soles. So if you want to run faster, you should buy shoes with thin soles, too!‚Äù

üßê What do you think about this example?
TreatAnecdotesQ3:
‚ö†Ô∏è This means that we need to be careful about anecdotes because they could lead us to the wrong conclusion. In fact, using anecdotes is a common tactic to persuade and manipulate.

üçí Anecdotes are often cherry-picked because something unusual happened. You don‚Äôt hear all the times that something didn‚Äôt work, because those stories aren‚Äôt as interesting.

üß† Humans are also more likely to remember personal stories, even if they aren‚Äôt as accurate.
